VALUES
(1, 46, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'And the sons of Levi; Gershon, Kohath, and Merari.', 0, 50, 'greek', 'Levi in Greek', 'Λευΐ (Leui, H3878) - Levi, meaning ''joined'' or ''attached''. This term reflects the significance of Levi''s role in being joined to God in service, which is foundational for understanding the Levitical priesthood and their duties.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3878", "description": "Strong''s number for Levi."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'And the sons of Judah; Er, and Onan, and Shelah, and Pharez, and Zerah: but Er and Onan died in the land of Canaan.', 0, 115, 'connection', 'Judah''s Lineage and Legacy', 'This passage connects to Matthew 1:3, where Judah''s line is traced to Jesus. The mention of Er and Onan’s deaths serves as a reminder of the consequences of sin (Genesis 38). Their story emphasizes God''s sovereignty in preserving a lineage despite human failings, ultimately leading to the Messiah.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 1:3", "description": "The genealogy of Jesus highlights the importance of Judah''s descendants."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'And the sons of Pharez were Hezron and Hamul.', 116, 161, 'theology', 'The Significance of Pharez', 'Pharez''s lineage is significant as it represents redemption and God''s grace. Many scholars believe that the inclusion of Pharez, born from a union with Tamar, illustrates how God can redeem broken situations and bring forth His purposes. This reflects the theme of divine grace throughout Scripture.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the redemptive nature of Pharez''s story."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'but Er and Onan died in the land of Canaan.', 72, 115, 'question', 'Reflecting on Divine Judgment', 'What does the death of Er and Onan reveal about God''s view on righteousness and obedience? How might this understanding influence our perspective on living a life pleasing to God?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'And the sons of Judah; Er, and Onan, and Shelah, and Pharez, and Zerah:', 0, 71, 'greek', 'Meaning of ''Judah''', 'יְהוּדָה (Yehudah, H3063) - Judah, meaning ''praised''. This name reflects the purpose of Judah''s lineage, which ultimately leads to the praise of God through the Messiah. The connection between Judah''s name and his descendants emphasizes God''s plan through praise.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3063", "description": "Strong''s number for the name Judah."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'And the sons of Issachar; Tola, and Phuvah, and Job, and Shimron.', 0, 65, 'connection', 'Issachar''s Significance', 'The mention of Issachar and his sons connects to Genesis 49:14, where Jacob prophesies that Issachar is a strong donkey, symbolizing hard work and service. This connection illustrates the character and future role of Issachar''s descendants within the tribes of Israel, emphasizing their labor and commitment to the community.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 49:14", "description": "Jacob''s blessing and prophecy for Issachar."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'Tola, and Phuvah, and Job, and Shimron', 26, 64, 'theology', 'Names and Their Meanings', 'Many scholars believe that the names of Issachar''s sons hold theological significance, reflecting attributes of God''s provision and blessing. Tola, meaning ''worm'', may symbolize humility, while Job, meaning ''persecuted'', suggests resilience. This highlights the diverse experiences within God''s chosen people, demonstrating how each lineage contributes to the larger narrative of redemption.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Insight on the meanings of the names in the context of God''s people."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'And the sons of Issachar;', 0, 25, 'question', 'Understanding Lineage', 'What does the listing of Issachar''s sons reveal about God’s design for family and community? How might their roles and characteristics inform our understanding of our own contributions within our communities today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'And the sons of Zebulun; Sered, and Elon, and Jahleel.', 0, 54, 'connection', 'Zebulun''s Role in Israel', 'The mention of Zebulun and his sons can be cross-referenced with Deuteronomy 33:18-19, where Moses blesses the tribe of Zebulun, highlighting their role in maritime trade and prosperity. This connection emphasizes the significance of Zebulun not just as part of Jacob''s lineage, but as a pivotal tribe in Israel''s future economic activities, reflecting God''s providence in the allocation of land and responsibilities.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 33:18-19", "description": "Moses'' blessing of the tribe of Zebulun."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'Zebulun', 16, 23, 'greek', 'Meaning of Zebulun', 'The name ''Zebulun'' is derived from the Hebrew זְבוּלוּן (Zevulun, H2074), which means ''dwelling'' or ''habitation.'' This reflects the tribe''s connection to settlement and stability in the Promised Land. The meaning of names in Scripture often carries significant implications for understanding character and destiny.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2074", "description": "Strong''s number for Zebulun."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'Sered, and Elon, and Jahleel', 25, 53, 'theology', 'Tribal Identity and Legacy', 'The listing of Zebulun''s sons—Sered, Elon, and Jahleel—highlights the importance of lineage and family identity in biblical theology. Many scholars believe that this lineage emphasizes God''s covenantal promise to multiply and bless the families of Israel, ensuring their legacy and role in the unfolding narrative of salvation history.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'Zebulun', 16, 23, 'question', 'What Does Zebulun Represent?', 'Considering Zebulun''s name and his descendants, what does it mean for us today to recognize our own ''habitation'' in Christ? How can we reflect the blessings of our spiritual heritage in our communities?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'These be the sons of Leah, which she bare unto Jacob in Padan–aram, with his daughter Dinah: all the souls of his sons and his daughters were thirty and three.', 0, 159, 'connection', 'Family Lineage Importance', 'The mention of Leah''s sons and daughter emphasizes the significance of family lineage in biblical narratives. This connects to Matthew 1:2-3, where the genealogy of Jesus highlights the importance of familial ties and heritage in God''s plan of redemption. Such lists serve not only historical purposes but also affirm God''s faithfulness in fulfilling His promises through generations.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 1:2-3", "description": "Genealogy of Jesus emphasizing lineage"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'with his daughter Dinah', 68, 91, 'theology', 'Role of Women in Lineage', 'Dinah''s inclusion in the genealogy reflects the value placed on women in biblical narratives. Many scholars believe this underscores the idea that women play significant roles in God''s redemptive history, which is often overlooked in patriarchal contexts. This inclusion invites readers to consider the broader implications of gender roles in Scripture.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "The New Bible Commentary", "description": "Discussion on women''s roles in biblical genealogies"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'all the souls of his sons and his daughters were thirty and three.', 93, 159, 'question', 'Significance of Numbers', 'What does the number thirty-three signify in the context of Jacob''s family? Reflecting on biblical numerology, thirty-three could represent completeness or fulfillment. How does understanding this number enrich your view of God''s provision and the establishment of His covenant community?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'And the sons of Gad; Ziphion, and Haggi, Shuni, and Ezbon, Eri, and Arodi, and Areli.', 0, 85, 'connection', 'Gad''s Significance', 'Gad, one of the tribes of Israel, is mentioned in Genesis 49:19, where Jacob prophesies that Gad will be raided but will raid back. This connection highlights the enduring legacy of Gad''s descendants and their role in Israel''s history, emphasizing themes of struggle and resilience. Additionally, Deuteronomy 33:20-21 praises Gad for being a great warrior, further underscoring the tribe''s importance in the context of Israel''s battles.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 49:19", "description": "Jacob''s prophetic words about Gad."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 33:20-21", "description": "Moses'' blessing of Gad."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'Gad', 16, 19, 'greek', 'Name Meaning', 'גָּד (Gad, H1410) - fortune, troop. The name reflects the significance of Gad''s lineage, as it is associated with both abundance and military prowess. This connection serves to highlight the dual aspects of Gad''s character as both blessed and a warrior tribe.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1410", "description": "Strong''s number for Gad."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'Ziphion, and Haggi, Shuni, and Ezbon, Eri, and Arodi, and Areli.', 21, 85, 'theology', 'Diversity in God''s People', 'The listing of Gad''s sons illustrates the diversity within God''s chosen people. Many scholars believe this highlights the importance of each individual and family within the larger narrative of Israel, suggesting that every person has a unique role and contribution to the community of faith.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'And the sons of Gad;', 0, 20, 'question', 'Role of Family Legacy', 'What does the mention of Gad''s sons teach us about the importance of family legacy in our spiritual journey? How might recognizing our own heritage influence our identity and purpose within the community of believers?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'the sons of Asher; Jimnah, and Ishuah, and Isui, and Beriah, and Serah their sister', 4, 87, 'connection', 'Tribe of Asher''s Significance', 'The mention of Asher''s sons in Genesis 46:17 connects to Deuteronomy 33:24-25, where Moses blesses the tribes. Asher is described as blessed with richness and favor, emphasizing the tribe''s importance in Israel''s future. This connection highlights the fulfillment of God''s promises to Jacob regarding his descendants.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 33:24-25", "description": "Moses'' blessing of the tribe of Asher"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'Serah their sister', 69, 87, 'theology', 'Role of Women in Genealogy', 'The inclusion of Serah, Asher''s daughter, indicates the significant role women play in biblical genealogies. Many scholars believe this reflects a broader theological perspective that acknowledges women''s contributions to God''s covenant people, suggesting that all members of the family, regardless of gender, partake in the blessings and responsibilities of the covenant.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'the sons of Asher', 4, 21, 'question', 'Understanding Family Legacy', 'What does the listing of Asher''s sons reveal about the importance of family legacy in our spiritual lives? How might recognizing our own family backgrounds influence our faith journey and our understanding of God’s promises?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'These are the sons of Zilpah, whom Laban gave to Leah his daughter, and these she bare unto Jacob, even sixteen souls.', 0, 118, 'connection', 'Family Lineage Importance', 'This passage highlights the importance of lineage in the biblical narrative, similar to Genesis 30:9-10, where Leah''s maid Zilpah bears sons for Jacob, emphasizing the theme of family and inheritance. Such connections are vital for understanding the fulfillment of God''s promises to Abraham regarding the multiplication of his descendants.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 30:9-10", "description": "Leah''s use of her maid Zilpah to bear Jacob''s sons"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'Zilpah, whom Laban gave to Leah his daughter', 22, 66, 'theology', 'Divine Providence in Family Dynamics', 'This verse illustrates the complex dynamics of family and divine providence. Many scholars believe that Zilpah''s role as a concubine reflects God''s sovereignty in using human relationships to fulfill divine plans, as seen in other instances where God uses unexpected means to accomplish His purposes.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses God''s sovereignty in family matters"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'even sixteen souls.', 99, 118, 'question', 'Understanding ''Sixteen Souls''', 'What does the number ''sixteen'' signify in the context of God''s covenant with Jacob''s family, and how does it reflect on the growth of the Israelite nation? Consider how this growth serves as a testament to God''s promises made to Abraham.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'The sons of Rachel Jacob’s wife; Joseph, and Benjamin.', 0, 54, 'connection', 'Rachel''s Legacy', 'The mention of Rachel and her sons Joseph and Benjamin connects to Genesis 30:22-24, where Rachel''s long struggle with barrenness concludes in joy as she bears Joseph and later Benjamin. This connection highlights the significance of Rachel''s role in the lineage of Israel, emphasizing God''s faithfulness in fulfilling His promises. Joseph''s later prominence in Egypt and Benjamin''s tribal importance are foundational to Israel''s history.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 30:22-24", "description": "Rachel''s prayer and God''s response regarding her children."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'The sons of Rachel Jacob’s wife; Joseph, and Benjamin.', 0, 54, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereign Plan', 'This passage illustrates God''s sovereignty in choosing specific individuals to fulfill His divine plan. Joseph''s story, filled with trials and triumphs, ultimately leads to the preservation of Israel during famine, reflecting how God''s purposes often unfold through unexpected circumstances. Many scholars believe this highlights the theological theme of redemption that runs throughout Scripture.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Insights on God''s providence in the lives of biblical figures."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'The sons of Rachel Jacob’s wife; Joseph, and Benjamin.', 0, 54, 'question', 'Understanding Family Dynamics', 'How does the mention of Rachel as Jacob''s wife influence our understanding of family roles in biblical narratives? Considering the context of sibling rivalry and favoritism, what can we learn about the impacts of parental relationships on the lives of Joseph and Benjamin?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'Joseph in the land of Egypt', 9, 36, 'connection', 'Joseph''s Egyptian Context', 'Joseph''s experience in Egypt is pivotal in the narrative of Genesis. This verse connects to Genesis 37:36, where Joseph is sold into Egypt, and Genesis 50:20, where he acknowledges God''s sovereignty in using his time there for good. Understanding Joseph''s life in Egypt helps illustrate the theme of divine providence and redemption, emphasizing how God can use difficult circumstances for His purposes.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 37:36", "description": "Joseph''s transition to Egypt."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 50:20", "description": "Joseph''s reflection on God''s plan."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'Ephraim, which Asenath the daughter of Poti–pherah priest of On bare unto him.', 60, 138, 'theology', 'Significance of Ephraim', 'Ephraim''s birth in Egypt highlights God''s ability to bless His people even in foreign lands. Many scholars believe this foreshadows the inclusion of Gentiles in God''s family, as Ephraim becomes a representative tribe of Israel. This is aligned with the New Testament understanding of salvation being available to all nations, thus reflecting God''s overarching plan of redemption.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discussion on Ephraim''s significance."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'Asenath the daughter of Poti–pherah priest of On', 75, 123, 'question', 'Cultural Influence Reflection', 'How might Joseph''s marriage to Asenath, a priest''s daughter, influence his identity and leadership in Egypt? Consider how cultural and familial connections can shape our faith and mission. In what ways does this relationship challenge or enrich your understanding of God''s purposes in diverse contexts?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'And the sons of Benjamin were Belah, and Becher, and Ashbel, Gera, and Naaman, Ehi, and Rosh, Muppim, and Huppim, and Ard.', 0, 122, 'connection', 'Tribe of Benjamin in Scripture', 'The names of Benjamin''s sons highlight the founding of the tribe of Benjamin, which plays a significant role in Israel''s history. Notably, King Saul, the first king of Israel, came from this tribe (1 Samuel 9:1-2). Additionally, the tribe is mentioned in the context of the New Testament, where Paul identifies himself as a Benjamite (Romans 11:1), illustrating the tribe''s enduring legacy.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Samuel 9:1-2", "description": "Introduction of Saul, the first king from Benjamin"}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Romans 11:1", "description": "Paul''s identification with the tribe"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'Belah, and Becher, and Ashbel, Gera, and Naaman, Ehi, and Rosh, Muppim, and Huppim, and Ard.', 30, 122, 'theology', 'Significance of Names', 'The names of Benjamin''s sons often carry meanings that reflect themes of struggle, favor, or divine purpose. For example, ''Gera'' means ''a grain'', which can symbolize sustenance and support for the tribe. Many scholars believe these names collectively represent the heritage and identity of the Benjamites, emphasizing God''s providence in their lineage and future.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Insights on the significance of biblical names"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'and Ard.', 114, 122, 'question', 'Reflection on Legacy', 'Why is the mention of Ard significant amidst the other sons? Each name represents a legacy and a story. What can we learn about our own legacy through the way these names are recorded? How might we be called to honor the names and stories of those who have gone before us?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'These are the sons of Rachel, which were born to Jacob: all the souls were fourteen.', 0, 84, 'connection', 'Rachel''s Significance', 'The mention of Rachel''s sons here connects to Genesis 30:22-24, where Rachel''s struggle with infertility and eventual blessing are highlighted. This is significant as it emphasizes God''s faithfulness in fulfilling His promises, particularly in the context of family lineage and the twelve tribes of Israel. Rachel is often seen as a pivotal figure in Jacob''s story, representing both hardship and divine favor.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 30:22-24", "description": "Rachel''s prayer and God''s response in granting her children."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'all the souls were fourteen.', 56, 84, 'theology', 'The Meaning of ''Souls''', 'The term ''souls'' here (Hebrew: nephesh, H5315) denotes living beings, which includes not only physical existence but also the spiritual essence of individuals. This verse suggests that each descendant carries not just lineage but also the weight of covenantal promise. Many scholars believe that this enumeration symbolizes the fullness of God''s chosen people, reinforcing the importance of family and heritage in the biblical narrative.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "The New International Commentary on the Old Testament", "description": "Explores the concept of ''nephesh'' and its implications."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'These are the sons of Rachel, which were born to Jacob:', 0, 55, 'question', 'Reflection on Family Legacy', 'What does it mean for us today to consider that Rachel''s sons were part of God''s redemptive plan? How does this understanding of family legacy influence our relationships and responsibilities within our own families?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'all the souls were fourteen.', 56, 84, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Souls''', 'נֶפֶשׁ (nephesh, H5315) - soul, living being, life. This term is essential in understanding the holistic view of life in the biblical narrative, indicating that each individual born carries significance beyond just their physical existence.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5315", "description": "Strong''s number for nephesh, indicating its use in various contexts."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And the sons of Dan; Hushim.', 0, 28, 'connection', 'Significance of Dan', 'The mention of Dan and his son Hushim connects to Genesis 49:16-17, where Jacob prophesies about Dan''s role as a judge among his people. This highlights the importance of Dan''s lineage in the broader narrative of Israel''s tribes and their destinies. Understanding this connection can deepen our appreciation of how each tribe contributed to the nation of Israel''s identity and function.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 49:16-17", "description": "Jacob''s prophecy about Dan"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And the sons of Dan; Hushim.', 0, 28, 'greek', 'Significance of Names', 'Although the Old Testament primarily uses Hebrew, the name ''Dan'' (דָּן, Dan, H1835) means ''judge.'' This signifies his role in the family and tribe, emphasizing the concept of justice within the covenant community. The name Hushim, while less clear in meaning, represents the continuation of Dan''s legacy.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1835", "description": "Strong''s number for the name Dan"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And the sons of Dan; Hushim.', 0, 28, 'theology', 'Tribal Identity in Israel', 'This verse reflects the broader theological theme of tribal identity in Israel, where each tribe has its unique role and destiny. Many scholars believe this lineage serves to illustrate God''s plan through a diverse community, where each tribe contributes to the whole. Such distinctions remind us of the value of each person''s calling within the body of Christ today.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discussion on the significance of tribal identities"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And the sons of Dan; Hushim.', 0, 28, 'question', 'Role of Tribes Today', 'What does the mention of Dan and his lineage teach us about the importance of community and individual roles within the church? How can we apply the lessons of tribal identity and purpose to our own lives and the way we serve together in faith?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'And the sons of Naphtali; Jahzeel, and Guni, and Jezer, and Shillem.', 0, 68, 'connection', 'Tribe of Naphtali', 'The listing of Naphtali''s sons directly connects to the later establishment of the tribes of Israel. Naphtali is one of the tribes that will receive land in Canaan (Joshua 19:32-39). This connection matters as it highlights the fulfillment of God''s promise to Jacob and the significance of lineage in the history of Israel.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Joshua 19:32-39", "description": "Details the inheritance of the tribe of Naphtali."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'Jahzeel, and Guni, and Jezer, and Shillem.', 26, 68, 'theology', 'Significance of Names', 'Many scholars believe that the names of Naphtali''s sons carry meanings that reflect the nature of God''s blessings and the experiences of the tribe. For instance, ''Jezer'' can mean ''he helps,'' suggesting divine assistance. This highlights the theological theme of reliance on God’s support throughout the journey of Israel.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'And the sons of Naphtali;', 0, 25, 'question', 'Understanding Lineage', 'What does the mention of Naphtali’s lineage teach us about the importance of family and heritage in our spiritual journey? How do these names reflect the broader narrative of God''s faithfulness to His people?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'Jahzeel, and Guni, and Jezer, and Shillem.', 26, 68, 'greek', 'Names and Identity', 'While this verse is in Hebrew, the concept of names representing character and destiny is prevalent in biblical texts. In Greek, the term ''ὄνομα'' (onoma, G3686) means ''name'' and can signify authority, character, or reputation. This insight encourages reflection on how names and identity shape our understanding of ourselves in relation to God.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G3686", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek word for ''name.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'These are the sons of Bilhah', 0, 28, 'connection', 'Bilhah''s Role in Genesis', 'This phrase connects to Genesis 30:3, where Rachel offers Bilhah to Jacob to bear children on her behalf. This highlights the cultural practice of surrogacy in ancient times and God''s providence in fulfilling Rachel''s desire for children, which is significant in understanding family dynamics in Genesis.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 30:3", "description": "Rachel''s use of Bilhah to fulfill her desire for children"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 46, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'which Laban gave unto Rachel his daughter', 30, 71, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty in Family', 'This passage suggests that Laban''s actions, though seemingly manipulative, are part of God''s sovereign plan for Jacob''s family. Many scholars believe that this reflects the theme of divine purpose intertwining with human actions throughout Genesis, emphasizing God''s control over family lineage.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Insight on divine sovereignty in human affairs"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
